The paper proposes a method for analyzing EEG data to estimate drowsiness during driving, which involves using deep Q-learning to optimize a Q-learning task. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the machine learning (cs.LG) and human-computer interaction (cs.HC) sub-categories. Additionally, the paper involves analyzing brain-computer interface (BCI) data, which could fall under the neural and evolutionary computing (cs.NE) sub-category. The paper also mentions tailoring a deep Q-network for action proposition, which could fall under the computer vision (cs.CV) sub-category. Finally, the paper involves using reinforcement learning, which could fall under the artificial intelligence (cs.AI) sub-category.
